  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.9.1-stable`\r\nOS & Version: macOS 10.14.6\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nThe following contract is deployed on Ropsten at the address `0x7dfA1211953031429e80d64317F4cad4c097C78e`:\r\n```\r\npragma solidity ^0.5.4;\r\n\r\ncontract Test {\r\n\r\n    uint256 public state = 5;\r\n\r\n    function test() public {\r\n        uint256 local = 1;\r\n        if (local > local + state) {\r\n            revert(\"reverted\");\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nUsing a `geth` light node, one expect to call `test` function using Go bindings sucessfully.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nAll transactions calling `test` function of the above contract fails with `out of gas` error. Seems that gas limit is underestimated within [transact method](https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/accounts/abi/bind/base.go#L185). Worth to note, this situation only takes place when having `state` field as given. If removed and value `5` is used directly in the condition, all estimates are correct. Going down to the EVM level, it seems that the thing which makes the difference is the usage of the `SLOAD` opcode. All transactions which used it had wrong gas limit estimates.\r\n\r\nAn example [failing transaction](https://ropsten.etherscan.io/tx/0x7e63d35bfa02db15eafd26b059823bfa047aeedc7bcbeb75107fbeef371ea3e2) has a gas limit estimated as `21661`, but a [successful one](https://ropsten.etherscan.io/tx/0x5eef47dcab07ea636704965d7846d9dff0ada857db38e568c9fcf7b6df8ee6c7) consumed exactly `22053`.\r\n\r\nI've also checked gas estimates for `test` function calls using `web3`. Estimates were the same as the ones made by Go binding.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n1. Deploy the above contract on Ropsten\r\n2. Call `test` method using a Go binding generated for this contract.\r\n\r\n",
